Augustus said he was like ‘a little pint pot ¹.’ His hair had been black ², but was grizzled and receding from the temples when he wrote the Epistle to Maecenas. He suffered from sore eyes ³. His temper was quick but not resentful ⁴. He liked to sit huddled up with a book by the fire in winter and to lounge in the sun in summer ⁵. He liked good wine and plenty of sleep ⁶. In his youth he was ambitious of literary fame3 but having acquired celebrity and a com- petence‚ he felt in himself no creative impulse or mission, such as urged Milton to write⁷. Dr. Johnson’s is an instance of a not dissimilar temperament. F ew personalities in literature are so well known to us, and few, if any, are more amiable.
